TSCG does not claim to be a general-purpose prompt compression method. On natural language, statistical methods are superior. On prompt \emph{content} optimization (selecting demonstrations, reformulating instructions, restructuring pipelines), search-based systems like DSPy~\cite{khattab2023dspy} and SAMMO~\cite{schlegel2024sammo} operate on a fundamentally different axis---they optimize \emph{what} to say, while TSCG optimizes \emph{how} to say it structurally. These are complementary, not competing, objectives.

\textbf{Why the niche matters.} TSCG's target domain---structured prompt content in agentic tool-use systems---is both real and growing. Modern agent frameworks (LangChain, CrewAI, AutoGen) embed dozens of tool definitions in every API call, each consuming 100--500 tokens. A typical agent invocation with 30 tools consumes 3,000--25,000 tokens in tool schemas alone, \emph{on every call}. At production scale (millions of calls per day), this represents a substantial and recurring cost that no existing system addresses: the NAACL 2025 prompt compression survey~\cite{li2024prompt} evaluates no system on function-calling schemas. TSCG's unique infrastructure profile---27.7\,KB, zero dependencies, deterministic, browser-compatible, sub-millisecond execution---enables deployment as lightweight middleware in any agent framework without requiring GPU infrastructure, Python runtimes, or external API calls.

\subsection{Threats to Validity}

\textbf{Internal validity.} The automated correctness checkers used in the benchmark may contain errors that systematically favor or disfavor certain strategies. We mitigated this by manually verifying all checker outputs for the first run and spot-checking subsequent runs.

\textbf{External validity.} The 19-task core benchmark was designed to cover diverse capabilities but may not be representative of real-world prompt distributions. The domain-specific benchmarks (Phases 0--3, totaling 107 additional tests) partially address this by evaluating TSCG on long-context retrieval, RAG pipelines, and tool-use scenarios closer to production workloads. The multi-model evaluation across four models (Claude Sonnet 4, GPT-4o, GPT-5.2, Gemini 2.5 Flash) spanning three provider families (Anthropic, OpenAI, Google) extends external validity across model architectures and instruction-following training approaches. However, further evaluation on real-world prompt distributions at scale and on additional model families (Llama, Mistral) remains important future work.

\textbf{Construct validity.} Binary accuracy (correct/incorrect) is a coarse metric that does not capture the quality gradient of partial correctness. For tasks like summarization or creative writing, where correctness is not binary, alternative metrics would be needed.

\subsection{Comparison with Human Prompt Engineering}

An important question is whether TSCG produces prompts that outperform those crafted by expert human prompt engineers. Our benchmark uses Natural prompts written by the first author, which represent competent but not extensively optimized prompt engineering. A rigorous comparison would require prompts from multiple expert prompt engineers, optimized for each specific task and model---a study we leave for future work.

We note, however, that TSCG's value proposition is not solely about accuracy improvement over expert prompts. Even at accuracy parity, TSCG provides: (i) deterministic reproducibility, (ii) consistent token cost savings of 6.3\% on general-purpose prompts and up to 71.7\% on structured domains such as tool descriptions, (iii) zero per-prompt engineering effort, and (iv) formal guarantees about semantic preservation. These properties have independent practical value regardless of the accuracy differential.

\subsection{Future Directions}

\textbf{Model-adaptive optimization profiles.} The four-model evaluation reveals a clear spectrum of TSCG compatibility: Claude Sonnet 4 (full benefit), GPT-5.2 (near-full benefit, no significant degradation), GPT-4o (partial benefit, significant TSCG+SAD degradation), and Gemini 2.5 Flash (mixed, with Tool Use benefit but RAG and combined degradation). Developing model-specific profiles that selectively enable, disable, or modify principles based on the target model's known sensitivities is an immediate priority. Concretely, a model compatibility matrix could map each principle to an effectiveness score per model family: CFL format annotations would be enabled for Claude and GPT-5.2 but disabled for GPT-4o and Gemini; TPD tool compression would be enabled universally (beneficial or neutral on all four models); and ICoT RAG restructuring would be disabled for Gemini models. This matrix-driven approach would maximize cross-model benefit while avoiding known degradation patterns.

\textbf{Multi-turn optimization.} The current framework optimizes individual prompts. Extending TSCG to multi-turn conversations---where attention patterns span multiple exchanges and the model maintains state across turns---is a natural next step. CCP and CFL could be adapted to position critical information at turn boundaries.

\textbf{Multimodal prompts.} As LLMs increasingly support multimodal inputs (text + images + code), TSCG's principles could be extended to optimize the ordering and formatting of mixed-modality prompts.

\textbf{Reasoning models.} Models with explicit chain-of-thought reasoning (e.g., o1, o3-mini, Gemini 2.5 Pro) respond differently to TSCG's optimization. Our evaluation of Gemini 2.5 Pro confirmed this: the thinking model produced empty responses on all TSCG-optimized prompts, likely because TSCG's compression interferes with the model's reasoning token generation. Adapting TSCG for thinking models---potentially by preserving more verbosity in prompts or using thinking-mode-specific API parameters---is an important direction as reasoning models become more prevalent.

\textbf{Non-English languages.} Building language-specific filler pattern libraries and validating TAS tokenizer alignment across multilingual BPE tokenizers would extend TSCG's applicability to the global LLM user base.

\textbf{Learned fragility scores.} Replacing CAS's heuristic importance estimation with learned fragility scores (e.g., trained on a dataset of prompt-response pairs annotated with parameter criticality) could significantly improve the accuracy of fragility-based ordering and duplication decisions.

\textbf{Domain-specific optimization profiles.} The domain benchmarks demonstrate that TSCG's effectiveness scales dramatically with domain structure: from 6.3\% savings on general prompts to 71.7\% on tool descriptions. Developing specialized optimization profiles for high-value domains---including tool-use pipelines, RAG systems, agent frameworks, and code generation---could unlock substantial cost savings in production LLM deployments. The ADC, TPD, and ICoT transforms introduced in this work represent a first step, but systematic investigation of domain-specific transform compositions remains an open problem.

\textbf{Formal verification.} TSCG's deterministic nature makes it amenable to formal verification---proving that specific transforms preserve semantic equivalence under a formal semantics of prompts. This is a long-term direction that could provide certified prompt optimization.
